# DFL Error Handling

## Core Principle: Throw Hard

The framework is designed to catch and handle unhandled exceptions at the top level (`MainState`). Game code must NOT intercept structural failures -- let them propagate. The framework will:

1. Dispose the faulting container scope (cleaning up resources)
2. Report the exception via `IErrorReporter` (Sentry in production)
3. Show an error state via `IErrorStateController`
4. Restart the app loop

```
Game code throws
  -> Container scope disposes
    -> MainState catches
      -> IErrorReporter.CaptureException (Sentry)
      -> IMain.ShowingErrorPopup
      -> IErrorStateController.Run (error UI)
      -> IMain.DismissingErrorPopup
      -> Restart app loop
```

Do NOT short-circuit this pipeline by catching and swallowing exceptions.

## Prohibited: Generic catch-and-continue

Never catch `Exception` in a loop and continue. This turns structural failures (missing assets, broken config, null managers) into infinite retry loops.

```csharp
// BAD -- swallows all failures, loops forever on structural errors
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    try
    {
        await RunLevel(level, token);
    }
    catch (Exception e)
    {
        Log.Error("Level failed: {0}", e.Message);
    }
}

// GOOD -- use result-based flow control; child scope returns normally, parent loops
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    ResultV<TitleScreenResult> result = await _titleScreen.Run(token);
    if (result.IsValid && result.Value == TitleScreenResult.Quit) break;

    await RunLevel(level, token);
    // level completed or user quit to title -- loop back naturally
}
```

## Allowed catch patterns

| Pattern | When to use |
|---------|-------------|
| `catch (SpecificException)` + continue | Rare -- only when an interface contract requires exception-based signaling |
| `catch (OperationCanceledException)` + `throw` | Always rethrow cancellation |
| `try/finally` | Cleanup (unsubscribe, hide UI, unlock cursor) -- no exception suppression |
| `catch (Exception)` + `throw` | Wrapping with context, then rethrowing (rare) |

## Prohibited: Log.Error or Log.Warning as error handling

`Log.Error` and `Log.Warning` are diagnostic output, NOT error handling. If a condition is an error, throw. If it's a precondition violation, use `Log.Assert`.

```csharp
// BAD -- logs a warning and continues with broken state
if (view == null)
{
    Log.Warning("No view found, using default");
    return defaultResult;
}

// GOOD -- assert the precondition; throws in dev, compiles out in release
Log.Assert(view != null, "view != null");

// GOOD -- throw if this is a runtime error that can't be asserted away
if (config.SceneRef == null)
    throw new GameException("LevelDefinition has no scene reference assigned.");
```

## OperationCanceledException

Always rethrow `OperationCanceledException`. Never catch it without rethrowing -- it signals scope disposal and must propagate to the container.

```csharp
// BAD -- swallows cancellation, scope cleanup breaks
catch (OperationCanceledException) { }

// BAD -- generic catch swallows cancellation too
catch (Exception e) { Log.Error(e.Message); }

// GOOD -- explicit rethrow
catch (OperationCanceledException) { throw; }

// GOOD -- separate catch before generic (if generic is truly needed)
catch (OperationCanceledException) { throw; }
catch (Exception e) { /* wrap and rethrow */ throw new GameException("Context", e); }
```

## IErrorStateController

Games register an `IErrorStateController` in `MainArgs`. This is the ONLY place unhandled exceptions should be surfaced to the user:

- Development: log the exception with full stack trace, then return (let the framework restart)
- Production: show an error popup, wait for user acknowledgment, then return

The controller runs OUTSIDE the faulting container scope (it's already disposed). Do not attempt to access game state from the error controller.
